            "NT > Graph the wash-in curves for common inhaled anaesthetics and relate to Meyer-Overton graph",                         #              Agents with low solubility (e.g., desflurane B:G 0.43) have a steeper wash-in curve, reaching equilibrium faster, while agents with high solubility (e.g., halothane) have a more gradual curve, taking longer to equilibrate. Wash-in curve illustrates how quickly the concentration of a volatile anesthetic in the alveoli FA equilibrates with the concentration delivered in the inspired gas Fi, influenced by solubility (blood:gas partition coefficient), cardiac output, alveolar ventilation, and the concentration gradient, Cardiac Output (Blood Flow): A high cardiac output acts as a "sink," pulling more anesthetic agent away from the alveoli and into the tissues. This slows down the rate of alveolar wash-in.Alveolar Ventilation: Increased minute ventilation drives the anesthetic into the lungs more quickly, steepening the wash-in curve.
