            "What is sickle cell disease?",                                                                                             #             Chromosome 11, point mutation, adenine swapped for thymine, hydrophilic glutamin (on the outside of the globin polypeptide) replaced by hydrophobic valine, causing polymerisation of HbS when deoxygenated > sickling, erythrocytes lifespan from 120 days to 20 > anaemia            
            "NT > What are the pathophysiology of Thalassemia?",                                                                        #             Reduced or absent production of one of globin chains, Forms: α-thalassemia: deficient production of alpha globin component of hemoglobin, while beta thalassemia is a deficiency in the beta globin component. The severity of alpha and beta thalassemia depends on how many genes are faulty. Severe forms (fetal hydrops) are often fatal in the neonatal period; Symptoms include tiredness, pallor, bone problems, an enlarged spleen, jaundice, pulmonary hypertension, and dark urine. A child's growth and development may be slower, HbH disease presents as thalassemia intermedia. β-thalassemia: More commonly clinically significant. Thalassemia major (Cooley’s anemia) requires regular transfusions; minor forms are often asymptomatic. Main problems: ineffective erythropoiesis, chronic hemolysis, and hemosiderosis (iron overload due to transfusions). 2. Anesthesiological Focus Areas (EDAIC Checklist), Airway: The “thalassemia facies”; problem: bone marrow hyperplasia leads to facial skeletal deformities (prominent upper jaw, malocclusion); consequence: increased risk of difficult intubation; examination findings: Careful clinical evaluation (Mallampati, thyreomental distance), organ functions (consequence of hemosiderosis), Heart: The most common cause of death is cardiac hemosiderosis (heart failure, arrhythmias), Preoperative: Check echocardiogram/ejection fraction, Liver: Hemochromatosis-related liver cirrhosis, Endocrinology: Diabetes mellitus (pancreatic damage) and adrenal insufficiency, Tight intraoperative blood glucose monitoring, Hematology & Transfusion Anemia managemen, Splenectomy: Many patients have undergone splenectomy. This leads to an increased risk of sepsis  (especially OPSI syndrome), consider perioperative antibiotic prophylaxis and vaccination status; coagulation: both thrombocytopenia (in cases of splenomegaly) and thrombophilia are possible; contraindication: iron supplementation is absolutely contraindicated (risk of exacerbating hemosiderosis); preoperative optimization: For planned procedures, optimize metabolic status (HbA1c) and organ function (heart, liver)                                                                              
            "What are the circumventricular organs and what is their function?",                                                        #             No BBB, around venticles, with extensive and highly permeable capillaries, allowing them to sense changes in the blood and CSF composition, and to secrete hormones into the bloodstream, 1. Subfornical organ (SFO) - osmoregulation and cardiovascular regulation, 2. Organum vasculosum of the lamina terminalis (OVLT) - osmoregulation and thermoregulation, 3. Area postrema (AP) - vomiting center, 4. Pineal gland - melatonin secretion, 5. Median eminence - hormone release from the hypothalamus, 6. Neurohypophysis (posterior pituitary) - release of ADH and oxytocina
